am afraid the empirical data supports the supply-siders.  The large money supply and high taxes policy of the 70s saw employment and inflation move in the same direction, up to be specific.  Unfortunately, a lot of professors espouse demand-side economics and students swallow hook, line and sinker.<br>
<br>
In the 80s we saw inflation plummet as supply increased.  Huge growth as incentive to work hard increased.  Income tax revenue increases while taxes decreased.<br>
<br>
Clinton raised taxes in the 90s and the economy did not collapse.  Is that the empirical data you refer to?  The end of the cold war (thanks to Reagan) and the tech boom/bubble could have had something to do with that as well.  You get an “A” for asshole and a “B” for bullshit (hah, couldn’t resist).<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Point 7 applies directly to the Japanese economy, where the household savings rate is very high. Given the well-documented behavior of Japanese consumers, it should not surprise anyone that loose monetary policy would have little effect on consumer spending there.<br>
<br>
American households have never shown a similar propensity to hold money when interest rates are low (Americans have one of the lowest household savings rates in the world). Americans have always been willing to take on debt when money is cheap. If you've paid any attention at all to the mortgage market in the last 18 months, this is exactly what has happened. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Are you saying the influence of stimulus depends?  Wow, I did not know that.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://p075.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=bumraz@ascension10244>Bumraz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 321<br> <font color=#333333>(6/24/04 8:46 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://p075.ezboard.com/fascension10244frm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2705.topic&index=182>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Something interesting</span><hr size=1> I know that you're being deliberately obtuse.  The point in quoting the exact same article that you used to supposedly bolster your own argument, was that <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>that article didn't support what you said</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.  In fact, it said exactly the opposite. You claim that tax cuts are responsible for the current economic resurgence, your own example article says otherwise.  Grats you on lack of reading comprehension.<br>
<br>
A couple of other points:<br>
The USSR was on its way to collapse with or without Reagan.  The Soviets were spending an unconscionable portion of their GDP on military production, essentially starving their own people.  This had been the trend long before Reagan.  It was not a sustainable political model.  You might as well give Reagan credit for gravity.<br>
<br>
As for the effects of stimuli being different depending on the behaviour of consumers, clearly that's the case.  However, the willingness of American consumers to assume debt (which is exactly what they've done while the interest rates were down) argues strongly for monetary modulation of economic cycles in this country.  Saying that the Japanese behave differently under simular stimuli (as your article did) is irrelevant to this discussion. We're not discussing Junichirou Kiizumi and his economic plans, are we?<br>
<br>
Empirical data supports supply side economics? Really? Hmmm.  <br>
<br>
Why did the household private savings rate decline to 60% of its 70s level after the Reagan tax cuts (exactly opposite of what supply side theory predicts)?  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>In the 80s we saw inflation plummet as supply increased. Huge growth as incentive to work hard increased. Income tax revenue increases while taxes decreased.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Really?<br>
<br>
Why did multifactor non farm labor productivity grow at a pace an average of 65% more under Clinton and his tax increase, and corresponding deficit reduction, than it did under the Reagan tax cut and balloon of deficit spending(Bureau of Labor Statistics, Multifactor productivity Index 1980-2001)? Sooo either people were either working smarter, or harder during a time when supply side theory maintained they would have less incentive to do so.<br>
<br>
Why did the labor force grow at lower rate during the Reagan era as it did prior to Reagan (Bureau of Labor Statistics, total non-farm employees 1970-2004), and then higher again under Clinton? Again, this is *exactly* the opposite of what Supply Side theory would predict.<br>
<br>
^^^^<br>
This is the empirical data, in case you missed it =)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
Clinton raised taxes in the 90s and the economy did not collapse. Is that the empirical data you refer to?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Haha. The economy did more than &quot;not collapse.&quot; That was an incredibly good period for the US.<br>
<br>
It's convenient when you can find a few fringe academic voices that support the dogmatic doctrines of one's party, but let's not try to make it more than that.   <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://p075.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=bumraz@ascension10244>Bumraz</A> at: 6/24/04 11:52 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://p075.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=siclid>Siclid</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Administrator</span><br>  Posts: 1531<br> <font color=#333333>(6/24/04 11:21 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://p075.ezboard.com/fascension10244frm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2705.topic&index=183>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Something interesting</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Semantically that is a fair point. However, when I used the words rather obviously, I did so for a reason. Are you going to sit there and tell me you did not know that over one million non-farm payroll jobs have been created since the last round of tax cuts? Or that the growth we are seeing is huge?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The only point I really wanted to get across was that your post was hypocritical. You could leave the &quot;rather obviously&quot; part out and it wouldn't change anything.<br>
<br>
I didn't really mean to jump into the political foray on either side (although I suppose I did in the end). I dug up the data just to emphasize the point that you did not provide data, contrary to your own admonition.<br>
<br>
One thing I'll agree with is that economics isn't an exact science. There's tons of data, but really no way to do an experiment. So every study you do is going to have a lot of uncontrolled variables; some will even be unknown. So, in the end, we're really looking at correlations, not cause and effect. Which can lead to fallacies such as the pet example &quot;higher ice cream sales cause increases in rapes,&quot; and in the end, you or I really can't prove a thing.<br>
<br>
But I bet you already knew all this, so I'll shut up.   <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :b --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":b"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
